    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here are the accounting policies for the requested areas:\n\n### 1. **Satellite Manufacturing Costs**\n   - **Capitalization Criteria**: Satellite costs include parts, labor, and allocated overhead. Launch costs incurred by the Space segment to deploy satellites to orbit are also capitalized.\n   - **Interest Capitalization**: Significant interest costs associated with the acquisition/construction of satellites are capitalized once activities to prepare the asset for intended use begin. Capitalization uses:\n     - Average accumulated expenditures during the preparation period.\n     - A capitalization rate derived from the weighted average borrowing rate (if no specific borrowings exist).\n   - **Ceasing Capitalization**: Stops when substantially completed and ready for use.\n   - **Depreciation**: Capitalized interest becomes part of historical cost, depreciated over the satellite’s useful life.\n   - **Useful Life Estimates**:\n     - **Broadband satellites**: 5 years.\n     - **First-generation mobile satellites**: 3 years.\n     - Based on engineering studies, on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization, design enhancements, and planned technology transitions.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E)**\n   - **Valuation**: Stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.\n   - **Depreciation Methods**:\n     - **Straight-line** over estimated useful lives, **except**:\n       - **Flight vehicles**: Depreciated based on **expected number of average flights** (unit-of-production).\n       - **Leasehold improvements**: Over shorter of useful life or lease term.\n   - **Useful Lives** (Key Examples):\n     - Servers/networking: 5–6 years\n     - Satellites: 3–5 years\n     - Flight vehicles: 5–25 flights (depending on vehicle type)\n     - Data centers: 20–25 years\n     - Buildings: 30 years\n   - **Revision of Estimates**: Useful lives and flight expectations are periodically reviewed with engineering teams and adjusted as new data emerges.\n   - **Impairment**:\n     - Evaluated at the **lowest level with independent identifiable cash flows** (e.g., individual asset or cash-generating unit).\n     - Triggered by events/circumstances (e.g., changes in use, technological obsolescence, declining cash flows).\n     - Written down to fair value if carrying value exceeds recoverable amount.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Internal Costs Capitalization**\n   - **Capitalization Rules**:\n     - **Routine maintenance/repairs**: Expensed as incurred.\n     - **Significant refurbishments/renewals**: Capitalized **if they increase functionality, output, or expected life**. These are depreciated over the asset’s revised useful life.\n   - **Satellite Launch Costs**: Capitalized as part of satellite costs (see Section 1).\n   - **Starship Development**: Costs are **expensed as R&D** during the development stage. Capitalization is expected **post-commercialization** (e.g., when delivering payload to orbit).\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Spacecraft Production**\n   - **Reusability Classification**:\n     - **Reusable components** (e.g., boosters, Merlin engines, fairings, Dragon capsule): Classified as **PP&E** and depreciated to cost of revenue over expected flights.\n     - **Non-reusable components** (e.g., Falcon second stages): Classified as **inventory** and expensed at launch/assignment.\n   - **Starship**: Currently in development; costs are **expensed as R&D**. Raptor engines used in test flights are expensed when used.\n   - **Cost Allocation**:\n     - Launch costs for Starlink satellites are **capitalized within the Connectivity segment**, not recognized as Space revenue.\n     - Customer launch costs are recognized in **Space segment revenue** upon launch/deployment.\n\n---\n\n### Key Distinctions in SpaceX’s Policies:\n- **Flight-Based Depreciation**: Unique treatment for flight vehicles/spacecraft based on expected flights rather than time.\n- **Hybrid Capitalization/Expensing**: Development costs (e.g., Starship) are expensed until commercialization, then capitalized.\n- **Segment-Specific Accounting**: Costs are allocated across segments (e.g., Starlink launch costs capitalized in Connectivity).\n- **Impairment Focus**: Evaluated at granular levels due to specialized assets (e.g., individual flight vehicles).\n\nThese policies reflect SpaceX’s vertically integrated model and emphasis on reusability, with careful capitalization of costs tied to future revenue generation.',
