2026-06-10 16:48:54,527 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Hypothetical Analysis: $2B Orbital AI Compute Satellite Manufacturing Costs\n\n### Segment Adjusted EBITDA Formula (Per Filing)\n\nThe filing defines Segment Adjusted EBITDA as:\n\n**Segment Adjusted EBITDA = Segment Loss from Operations + D&A + SBC + Restructuring + Impairments**\n\nThis is a critical construct because D&A is added back, but operating expenses (including R&D and cost of revenue) are NOT.\n\n---\n\n### Quantifying the Difference\n\n#### **Scenario A: Capitalization Treatment**\n\n| Item | Impact |\n|:-----|:-------|\n| $2B recorded as PP&E (satellites) on balance sheet | No P&L impact at acquisition |\n| Depreciation over useful life (5 years per policy for broadband/similar satellites) | -$400M annual expense |\n| Impact on Segment Loss from Operations | -$400M |\n| D&A add-back in Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation | +$400M |\n| **Net Impact on Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$0** |\n\nThe capitalization path is "EBITDA-neutral" because the depreciation expense is added back in the reconciliation.\n\n#### **Scenario B: Expensing Treatment**\n\n| Item | Impact |\n|:-----|:-------|\n| $2B expensed immediately (as R&D or cost of revenue) | -$2,000M charge |\n| Impact on Segment Loss from Operations | -$2,000M |\n| No D&A to add back (not capitalized) | $0 |\n| **Net Impact on Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **-$2,000M** |\n\nThe expensing path reduces Adjusted EBITDA by the full $2B because the charge flows through operating expenses without a corresponding add-back.\n\n#### **Difference**\n\n| Treatment | Adjusted EBITDA Impact |\n|:----------|:----------------------|\n| Capitalization | $0 |\n| Expensing | -$2,000M |\n| **Difference** | **$2,000M** |\n\n**Capitalization produces $2.00 billion higher AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA than expensing in the year the costs are incurred.**\n\nThis differential arises entirely from the mechanical structure of the Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation: D&E is added back, but R&D and cost of revenue are not. Over the satellite\'s full useful life (5 years), cumulative Adjusted EBITDA impact converges—capitalization spreads the $2B as $400M annual depreciation add-backs for 5 years ($400M × 5 = $2B total add-back), while expensing is a one-time $2B hit. The timing difference is the source of the $2B divergence in the manufacturing year.\n\n---\n\n### Disclosed Accounting Policies Governing This Judgment\n\nThe filing identifies **four key policies** that would govern whether orbital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs should be capitalized or expensed:\n\n#### **1. Satellite Manufacturing Costs Policy**\n> "Satellite costs include parts, labor, and allocated overhead. Launch costs incurred to deploy satellites to orbit are also capitalized."\n\nThis policy presumes capitalization for operational satellites, but the threshold question is whether the satellites are "ready for intended use."\n\n#### **2. R&D Expensing Policy / Commercialization Threshold**\n> "The company expenses R&D costs as incurred. Capitalization begins only when activities to get an asset ready for its intended use have commenced."\n\nThe filing explicitly states that for assets under development (analogous to Starship), costs are **expensed as R&D until commercialization**—defined as the point when the asset is "deemed commercially operational and generating revenue."\n\n**This is the critical judgment point**: If orbital AI compute satellites are still in a development/pre-commercial phase, the $2B would be expensed as R&D. If they are commercially operational, the $2B would be capitalized as PP&E.\n\n#### **3. Property, Plant & Equipment / Useful Life Policy**\nIf capitalized, satellites are depreciated on a **straight-line basis** over estimated useful lives:\n- Broadband satellites: **5 years**\n- First-generation mobile satellites: **3 years**\n- Based on engineering studies, on-orbit performance, propellant life, and planned technology transitions\n\nFor AI compute satellites, the useful life estimate would directly affect the annual depreciation magnitude (though not the total Adjusted EBITDA impact over the full life).\n\n#### **4. Interest Capitalization Policy**\n> "Significant interest costs associated with the acquisition/construction of satellites are capitalized once activities to prepare the asset for intended use begin."\n\nIf the $2B manufacturing program involves significant financing costs, those would also be capitalized under this policy, further increasing the capitalized asset base and D&A.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|:---------|:-------|\n| Adjusted EBITDA difference (cap vs. expense) | **$2.00 billion** in the manufacturing year |\n| Direction | Capitalization is $2B higher |\n| Reason | D&A is added back in Adjusted EBITDA; R&D/COGS are not |\n| Primary governing policy | R&D expensing policy vs. satellite capitalization policy |\n| Key judgment threshold | Whether satellites are "commercially operational and generating revenue" vs. in development stage |\n| Filing useful life assumption | 3–5 years for satellites |\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation tables (MD&A – Non-GAAP Financial Measures)\n- Significant Accounting Policies (Satellite Manufacturing Costs; PP&E; R&D Capitalization)'})
